    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{y}{y-3}} = {4} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{4\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of all fractions in this equation, we multiple all terms with the common denominator. In this equation, the common denominator is <m>{y-3}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{y}{y-3}} \amp = {4} \\
   {\frac{y}{y-3}} \cdot ({y-3}) \amp = {4} \cdot ({y-3}) \\
   y \amp = 4y - 12 \\
   y \mathbf{-4y} \amp = 4y - 12 \mathbf{-4y} \\
   -3y \amp = -12 \\
   \frac{-3y}{-3} \amp = \frac{-12}{-3} \\
   y \amp = 4
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. By the original equation, the domain condition is <m>y - 3 \ne 0</m>, or <m>y \ne 3</m>. This doesn<rsq/>t conflict with the solution above, so the solution is <m>y = 4</m>.</p>
</solution>
